04333nmm a2200577Ia 9780801454516DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979740735  a97808014545167 a10.7591/97808014545162doi  a(DE-B1597)478573  a(OCoLC)904979076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a305.895/105912231 aChang, Wen-Chin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Borders :bStories of Yunnanese Chinese Migrants of Burma /cWen-Chin Chang. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b13 halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Yunnanese from southwestern China have for millennia traded throughout upland Southeast Asia. Burma in particular has served as a "back door" to Yunnan, providing a sanctuary for political refugees and economic opportunities for trade explorers. Since the Chinese Communist takeover in 1949 and subsequent political upheavals in China, an unprecedented number of Yunnanese refugees have fled to Burma. Through a personal narrative approach, Beyond Borders is the first ethnography to focus on the migration history and transnational trading experiences of contemporary Yunnanese Chinese migrants (composed of both Yunnanese Han and Muslims) who reside in Burma and those who have moved from Burma and resettled in Thailand, Taiwan, and China. Since the 1960s, Yunnanese Chinese migrants of Burma have dominated the transnational trade in opium, jade, and daily consumption goods. Wen-Chin Chang writes with deep knowledge of this trade’s organization from the 1960s of mule-driven caravans to the use of modern transportation, and she reconstructs trading routes while examining embedded sociocultural meanings. These Yunnanese migrants’ mobility attests to the prevalence of travel not only by the privileged but also by different kinds of people. Their narratives disclose individual life processes as well as networks of connections, modes of transportation, and differences between the experiences of men and women. Through traveling they have carried on the mobile livelihoods of their predecessors, expanding overland trade beyond its historical borderlands between Yunnan and upland Southeast Asia to journeys further afield by land, sea, and air.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChinesexMigrations. 0aChinesezBurma. 0aColonies and colonization. Emigration and immigration. International migration. 0aMuslimszBurma. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies.  acaravan trading, gendered trading lives, chinese origin, southwestern china, chinese trade, chinese political refugees, chinese communism, yunnanese refugees, chinese migration.2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801454516?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801454516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801454516/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aGBV-deGruyter-alles